<br>
Actually, &quot;ye, doth, goeth&quot; is Early Modern English (roughly 1500-1800 AD).  Notable examples are Shakespeare (born 1564, died 1616), Queen Elizabeth (1533-1603) and the King James Bible (translated 1604-1611).  Old English was spoken from the fifth to the eleventh century AD and is essentially a foreign language.  It bears about as much resemblance to modern English as, say, German.<br>
<br>
Being that fantasy is traditionaly set in medieval times (roughly 400-1500 AD), if anything, &quot;ye, doth, goeth&quot; would be too modern.  It would be more accurate to speak <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://icg.fas.harvard.edu/~chaucer/teachslf/gp1-18tr.htm" target="top">Middle English</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, or even <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.georgetown.edu/labyrinth/library/oe/texts/a4.1.html" target="top">Old English</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>/pedantic off</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Brunhild Twinaxe, rabbi of Brell<br>
Lux Aeternam secretary<br>
